ion is warranted. While recognizing the many successes of the “Vancouverism” model, the contributors acknowledge that the forces of globalization and speculative property development have increased social inequality and housing insecurity since the 1980s in the city and the region. To determine the city’s prospects for overcoming these problems, they look at city planning from all angles, including planning for the Indigenous population, environmental and disaster planning, housing and migration, and transportation and water management. By looking at policies at the local, provincial, and federal levels and taking reconciliation with Indigenous peoples into account, Planning on the Edge highlights the kinds of policies and practices needed to reorient Vancouver’s development trajectory along a more environmentally sound and equitable path.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCity planningzBritish ColumbiazVancouver. 0aSociology, UrbanzBritish ColumbiazVancouver. 0aSustainable developmentzBritish ColumbiazVancouver. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aAngeles, Leonora C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBigazzi, Alexander Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChang, Stephanie E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdelson, Nathan J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeng, Lisi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, Lawrence D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedmann, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Larissa, econtributor.4c